<div id="outline-container-orgfe803b1" class="outline-2">
<h2 id="orgfe803b1">Questions</h2>
<div class="outline-text-2" id="text-orgfe803b1">
<p>
Clearly something needs to be done. ACORN UK is a large organisation that attracts high number of socialists/communists/anarchists/marxists/etc, many ex-Corbyn people who are disillusioned with the Labour party. ACORN as it currently stands seems to be pissing away the potential to build something effective to fight for tenants power. Is this something that can happen in ACORN? How do activists engaged in carrying out this work from inside ACORN do so in a way that doesn't get scrapped when ACORN National fall out with a branch and destroy it completely?
</p>

<p>
Are the former committee of the my branch, and the former-Lancaster branch correct that Acorn is un-reformable? It also seems that the anarchist behind the LibCom article don't think that . If they believe this to be the case, can someone make it clear why this is the case? If you can demonstrate this, and make the argument, then there is no reason for anyone to remain in Acorn and I will cancel my membership today.
</p>

<p>
If Acorn reformable? The people who have stayed in Acorn, despite coming across the evidence of its dysfunction,
</p>
</div>
</div>

